Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists from the University of California in Santa Cruz have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow to look for among the stars related, that is, arising from the same cluster.
The authors published the results of their research in the journal Nature, and they can be briefly read on the website of the university.
The reason for the identical chemical composition of the nearest stars is the turbulent mixing in gas clouds that precedes the formation of stars.
Even if a born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of birth and the region of formation of relatives.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
Simulation results conducted by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, scientists used a supercomputer to simulate two interstellar gas streams that together formed a cloud.
This object for several million years under the action of its own gravity is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added labels to the original gas flows and found that a high degree of chemical homogeneity was achieved due to rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud.
According to astrophysicists, their research proves that it is possible to look for relatives of stars by chemical composition, as well as to identify possible regions of formation of such objects.
