Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a bill that would protect trade unions as a civil law.
“Where trade unions are, there are middle-class jobs,” says Allison, a Democrat from Minnesota who is a congressional co-chair of the Progressive Faction.
That’s why I’m proud to present the Workers’ Rights Expansion Act along with the civil rights movement symbol John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give employees the same legal opportunities when discriminating against trade unions as in other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of opponents of trade unions.
Changing the Labour Relations Regulation Act in such a way as to allow workers facing discrimination for participating in trade unions to seek justice in civil courts – and to receive damages and fines – is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is undoubtedly not a radical initiative – at least according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to figure out what Allison, Lewis and the co-authors of the bill are offering is to recall a very American idea.
Despite the attacks facing trade unions in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country — Americans once supported countries around the world in adopting, expanding and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas McArthur and his assistants helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the militant autocracy of Hideki Tojo was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions play a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly acknowledged that “the right of workers to organize, and to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his assistants helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article which openly stated: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve labor and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or sphere of activity.
Agreements which restrict or seek to prejudice this right shall not have legal force; measures aimed at these purposes shall be deemed unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was to be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global agreement, Roosevelt and its authors included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to organize and join unions to defend their interests.”
For generations, Americans have taken the basic position that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions – and that the trade union should participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies – should be protected.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is wise, indeed, to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As St. Martin Luther King said 50 years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the strength of the nation, but has increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, the trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and lifted the whole nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers as we should.
The official recognition of labor rights as human rights – and the expansion of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination against trade unions – has long been obsolete.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis revive the ideals that historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
A judge temporarily blocks a law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the implementation of the Louisiana law, which supporters say is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under this measure, which was signed for enforcement by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginnald in June and was to come into force on September 1, doctors who do abortions would be required to have authorization to receive patients in hospitals within a radius of 30 miles from their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that at the moment doctors can continue to do legal abortions while continuing to seek such authority.
"The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing the proceedings to obtain authority," Judge John DeGravels wrote in his decision.
The hearing will be appointed within a month, during which the judge will make a more permanent decision on this law.
Defenders of the right to abortion welcomed this decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital authorities.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from a false law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a lawsuit on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics.
It was not immediately obvious whether the decision applied to doctors from two clinics who did not act as plaintiffs in this case and also filed for authorization for admission.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts recently recognized such measures as unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would close most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Fighters for the right to abortion, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admissions laws impose restrictions on doctors that are not necessary from a medical standpoint.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women’s health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has authority for hospital admission, the Reproductive Rights Center said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop doing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop doing it, the group said.
Criticising the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who do abortions as long as their applications for admission authority are awaiting a decision.
