Almost a month later, we can talk about increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as rising prices for finished products,” said the first vice president of the All-Russian public organization “Russian Club of Financial Directors”, K.E.N. Tamara Kasyanova.
The idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food goods in each category will allow the sector to be fixed on local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that are cheaper at the expense of subsidies from another state.
In other words, the battle for the buyer will unfold between companies operating under uniform laws of the industry.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian manufacturers are able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots far from all articles.
And in this situation, the retail chains will have to "reach" the share of Russian goods to half the range.
In this regard, there are growing fears that low-quality goods will arrive on the shelves.
Per under the guise of Russian products will be supplied foreign products with broken labels", - adds the expert.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large trading networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that with this arrangement, foreign suppliers themselves will suffer because the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas for domestic goods may affect consumers as well.
The fact is that some products of Russian production may be inferior in quality to imported analogues, while stores will be able to raise prices for the latter, as for a deficient product.
The idea of import substitution, which was forgotten in the early 2000s, was again discussed by economists in February of this year due to the continued devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the backdrop of difficult relations with the West, the issue of refusing imported products is becoming even more relevant.
The law is intended to obligate retailers when forming orders to suppliers to count with domestic producers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently on the path of import substitution, and the system of production planning for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time," says Deputy Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be especially effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is high, for example, in the dairy industry, where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really able to fully cover the shelves of Russian stores.
Meat production can also get a strong impetus.
As is known, the largest share of imports is retained by beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out, 65-70% still falls on Russian products", - explains Kasyanova.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas on domestic products will promote import substitution and can speed up this process.
However, in itself, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, as this requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is confident.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be brought from abroad, which means that a full-fledged import substitution will not occur, but significant steps in this direction will be made.
In addition, it is not enough to establish quotas, it is still necessary to set up domestic production in the country in order to meet these quotas.
These quotas will provide such guarantees,” the expert says.
Late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James published a video of the memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who forgive in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
Researchers analyzed disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after the diagnosis was made.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Institute for Medical Research Berghofer that the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher in those living in regions and remote areas of the state than in those living in urban areas.
Small Study: New Drugs May Slow Lung Cancer and Ovarian Cancer
The researchers followed the medical path of women over seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that the age of the woman at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also influenced the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not intended to determine why women living outside cities were more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment were possible factors.
“This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in large cities,” she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of services at departure, which will allow professionals to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people undergoing treatment away from their home, could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study found that longer life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
