The largest Chinese companies unite against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China’s largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and Internet giants Tencent Holdings (social networks, messengers, etc.) and Baidu (the largest Chinese search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
However, to catch up with the miracle of the Chinese Internet, which has left behind even its American rivals - eBay and Amazon.com, will not be easy.
Union of the largest
The two companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of which will belong to Wanda and 15% to each of the Internet companies, the Wanda Group said in a statement.
The company will be registered in Hong Kong.
SP will combine Baidu’s search services with popular social platform WeChat (China’s largest social network with about 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 fashionable hotels, Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial real estate facilities across China and 40 shopping centers.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan ($8 billion) in the construction of a film studio and theme park in Qingdao (a city in eastern China on the Yellow Sea).
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate a profit of $960 million.
In addition, Wanda owns the American network of cinemas AMC Entertainment Holdings, which makes the company the largest operator of cinemas in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all of its own shopping centers, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by the competitor Alibaba.
According to Dun Ce, who will lead the new company, thanks to the merger Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year.
The new platform is expected to become the world’s largest online-to-offline platform, says Dun Zi.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract online buyers to come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O are coupons selling services such as Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
"O2O is the biggest "cake" in online commerce," said Wanda chief executive Van Jianglin (cited by Bloomberg).
"Now there is no real O2O platform in China, and in this situation the chances are roughly equal," he believes.
The Chinese online trading market is the largest in the world, and McKinsey & Co. estimates its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese internet users has grown to 632 million, according to Bloomberg official statistics: this is more than the population of any country in the world except India.
And according to the forecasts, by 2015 this number could grow to 850 million people.
Union of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huaten was until recently the richest man in China, but according to Bloomberg’s Millionaires Index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already surpassed him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma’s fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion comes from his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu chief Robin Lee now ranks third among the wealthiest people in China, while Wang Jianlin of Wanda is fourth in the ranking.
“It’s very interesting to watch behind this battle: the three richest people are joining forces to challenge the even richer one,” said Bloomberg director of the Chinese e-commerce research center in Hangzhou, Tsao Lee.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to be able to seriously compete with Alibaba immediately after its creation: "Rome cannot be built in a day."
The fact that it is not so easy to compete with Alibaba not only new companies, but also the well-deserved leaders of the world internet trade, is evidenced by the published report on Alibaba's financial performance for the last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as something of the middle between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June the Chinese company earned more than both of its American competitors combined.
Alibaba’s net profit for the period almost doubles the similar summary of competitors – it grew almost three times in annual terms and amounted to $1.99 billion.
“Alibaba still has enormous money-generating potential, largely thanks to its mobile apps,” said an analyst at Hong Kong’s Arete Research Service.
According to the updated prospectus of Alibaba on the website of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of active mobile users of the company's services in July amounted to 188 million, which is significantly higher than the March figure (163 million people).
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions in the last quarter came from mobile devices.
Alibaba will have to name the value of its shares before the IPO.
According to an average estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the sale of shares.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba’s debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) may take place on September 16.
The company’s road-show, which precedes this event, starts on September 3.
Alibaba’s IPO is expected to be a record in the history of the NYSE and will allow the company to raise around $20 billion.
Until now, the record for the amount of funds attracted on the US exchanges belonged to the Visa payment system, which in 2008 held the primary placement of its shares, earning $ 17.9 billion.
At least half of food products in retail chains should be of Russian production, according to deputies of the State Duma.
They have drafted a bill on the subject.
Article 8 of the Federal Law “On the Basics of State Regulation of Trade Activities in the Russian Federation” and the Tax Code.
The aim of the document is to introduce protective measures against Russian food producers.
Important clarification, according to the bill, at least 50 percent of products of domestic production in the stores must be for each type of goods.
However, the document will take into account that there are goods that are not produced in Russia, such as vegetables and fruits in the winter, so there will be a "discount" for them to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
At the same time, the draft law also amends the Tax Code of the Russian Federation, which establishes a reduced VAT rate of 10% for the sale of all food goods, the country of origin of which is Russia.
On August 27, a draft law on amendments to the Federal Law "On Retail Markets" was submitted to the lower house of the parliament, which proposes to revive farmers' markets in Russia, where small producers will be able to sell their products.
Magaluf police chief accused of corruption
The plaintiffs submitted evidence of extortion by police and officials of the municipality of Calvia to the office of the state prosecutor of Mallorca on Friday.
The chief of the Calvia police on the resort island of Mallorca was arrested as a result of allegations of corruption by businessmen and bar owners in the scandalously famous Magaluf drunkenness center.
Chief Inspector José Antonio Navarro has been placed in custody as a result of corruption charges raised against him by several businessmen from Punta Balena, the street where most of Magaluf's bars and nightclubs are located.
