The first day of spring is marked by wet and windy conditions that have affected flights at Adelaide Airport
Spring has prepared a cold surprise in southern South Australia, bringing heavy rains and strong winds that have affected flights at Adelaide Airport.
Another 5 mm of rain fell on the city in the evening at 9 p.m., following the 6.6 mm that fell over the night of Sunday.
The last rain was preceded by a couple of short rains with a whirlwind, including a thunderstorm that began shortly before 8 p.m. and poured out 4 mm in about 10 minutes.
After winter gave off the early portion of spring last week, temperatures fell again on Monday to a peak of just 15.8C in the city.
Bad conditions are believed to have been one of the reasons for the delay of the Virgin Airlines flight from Melbourne to Adelaide.
The plane was scheduled to land immediately after 7:30 p.m., but hit the wind shift zone - a sudden change in speed or wind direction on a short distance - and was forced to gain height.
Wind blows reached 50 km/h on the ground at Adelaide Airport at this time.
Flight data showed that the aircraft had to reach a height during the second landing, and the aircraft eventually landed around 8:40 p.m.
The delay caused subsequent delays on several other flights, including Emirates flights from Dubai and Qantas flights from Sydney.
A maximum of 16C is forecast in Adelaide on Tuesday with the likelihood of one or two rains.
The calculation of the estimate of construction facilities in the Russian Federation will take place in a new way
Issues of pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as problems of connection to networks the Federal Antimonopoly Service takes on special control.
The FAS established an expert council on the development of competition in the construction sector.
At his meeting, the head of the management of control of housing, construction and natural resources FAS Vadim Soloviev said that "today's calculation of the estimate of construction objects is absolutely incomprehensible."
The regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and can lead to unreasonable construction costs, according to the FAS.
And they propose the cost of construction of state-owned objects at the design stage to be determined on the basis of market prices of constructive solutions instead of the estimated norms and individual pricing for technological operations applied today.
These proposals are included in the road map and are currently being considered in the Ministry of Finance.
“The replacement of traditional estimate documentation in construction with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry,” explained Vadim Soloviev.
After all, now in the estimate each screw and gauge is calculated, and it is not always possible to check everything, so sometimes in the documentation unfair construction companies can bury "whole tractors".
I agree with FAS.
"The first work on the transition to the calculation of value on the constructive elements already exists: methods have been developed for the calculation of prices on the constructive solutions, the preparation of estimates on these indicators," said Elena Zhukova, Head of the Department of Urban Development and Architecture of the Ministry of Construction.
The road construction area was selected as a pilot.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
As the head of the construction company "Profi-invest" Anatoly Demyanko told "RGB", estimate standards have long been outdated, but another mechanism for business has not yet been proposed.
"As for the proposed calculations on the structural elements, this is difficult to implement in practice, because completely different technologies are often used in the construction of buildings," he said.
It is no secret that the construction market is developed in large part due to the state order.
According to the Chairman of the Board of State Procurement "Expert Community of Public Procurement Professionals" Ekaterina Lezina, today the state is the most solvent customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, deputy director of engineering of Rosatom’s industrial capital construction center, pointed out that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to a portfolio of contracts and companies that possess monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors to enter this field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only if access to contracts is protected as far as possible from someone’s governing influence.
At the expert council, it was proposed to form a system of state order in such a way that the same contractor is not entitled to receive more than one contract in the amount of more than 1 billion rubles. or several contracts in the amount of more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry of Construction believes that this approach needs to be assessed in terms of the impact on business, as well as the effectiveness of construction management.
As explained by Elena Zhukova, in this case it will be necessary to give the customer the functions of the general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the staff of the customer and budget expenses for its maintenance.
At the same time, the customer’s specialists will need to have the knowledge to assess the quality of the works performed by the contracting organizations, as well as their safety.
Often with such a breakdown, it will be necessary to determine who will be responsible for the safety of the object as a whole.
In addition, this approach can lead to the outflow of highly qualified participants in public procurement in connection with the uninterest in receiving the state order for the incomplete volume of works and the small amount of the contract.
Deputy head of the expert and consulting center of the Institute of Procurement Alexander Yevstašenkov believes that now the procedure of the state order has become a business game on the attention of the contractor.
When filling out the application, the participant must indicate "concrete indicators" without stating the words: "or equivalent", "should be", "from", "more", "less", "analogue", "or", "type", "analogue type", "not lower", "lower", "above", "can have", "may be", "not earlier", "not above", "not allowed" and so on.
Thus, customers often abuse their right to set requirements for the content of applications submitted by contractors.
Another problem of the 44-FZ, according to Evstachenkov, was the need to assess the quality of the work through the "paper" offer of the participant.
Considering the application of the participant, it is really possible to evaluate only the qualification of the contractor, but not the quality of the work, the performance of which has not even started, - believes the expert.
The quality of the work can only be assessed when it is accepted.
The expert council was also suggested to move margin income from the top to the bottom, so that intermediate contractors disappear.
The chairman of the expert council, state secretary, deputy head of the FAS Andrei Tsarikovsky believes that this is not worth doing, because the general contractor must be responsible for the order.
And otherwise it will be, as in the famous replay of Arkady Rykin "Atelier": "There are claims to the buttons?".
Israeli children return to school after Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in the territories near the Gaza Strip returned to school on Monday after spending a summer in bomb shelters when rockets and mines fell on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed while the territory was being restored after hostilities.
The start of school classes brought a sense of joy and excitement to the missile-affected settlements of southern Israel, but the traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, employees of the kindergarten "Pashosh", which hit the rocket, removed traces of fragments from the walls and children's hills before the arrival of students.
“We’re a little scared, but looking forward to the future with joy,” said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibuc Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to return to a measured life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said it was “a little strange” to start going to school again.
“It was a tough time and we didn’t leave our homes at all,” she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited Kibutz, which is located near the Gaza border, to express his support.
Before a ceasefire agreement stopped the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad did not go out or left their homes, moving to safer areas further from Gaza to escape rocket and mortar fires.
Many inhabitants of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a Palestinian mine, doubt whether they should return.
The Ministry of Education said about a dozen families have not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools at this time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the Gaza border that has been heavily damaged by the Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study diligently and said, "We will do our best to give you knowledge and ensure your safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed on an indefinite ceasefire on Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement immediately put an end to hostilities, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas’ demands to lift the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and to open airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its weapons and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of indirect talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
More than 2,100 Palestinians were killed in the war, three-quarters of whom were civilians, and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of the killed were militants; however, it has not provided substantial evidence supporting this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians were killed, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 units of missiles and mines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
As a result of Israeli attacks, thousands of houses in Gaza were damaged and destroyed, and an estimated 25,000 people have found refuge in more than 100 schools that have been converted into shelters.
Because tens of thousands of people were still in shelters and fighting continued, officials in charge of education postponed the start of the school year last week.
“I hope that the school will soon be opened so that we can complete our education as children around the world and Jewish children,” said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in one of the schools in Gaza.
According to the popular criterion, property prices showed the largest winter growth in seven years.
The RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic housing price index for housing prices in the Australian capital rose by 1.1 percent in August, RP data on Monday.
This increase resulted in a combined 4.2% increase in June, July and August, the largest increase in winter months since 2007.
Annual price growth was 10.9 percent, more than doubling the growth in 12 months as of August 2013, but the increase was not evenly distributed across the country.
Research director of RP Data, Tim Lawless, said Sydney and Melbourne are leading a two-tiered market.
RP Data figures show that housing prices have risen 16.1% in Sydney over the past year, compared to 11.7% in Melbourne.
The next markets in power were Adelaide, Brisbane and Darwin, where prices rose on average from five to six percent.
On the other end of the scale was Canberra, where government spending cuts followed, where prices rose by just 1.4 percent in the year.
Mr. Lawless said that now that spring has begun, there will be an increase in the number of properties on sale over the next few months, which will be a “real test” for the market.
"Given the current high rate of auction sales, the overall high rate of sales and the current conditions with low interest rates, it is likely that the price of housing will continue to rise over the next three months," he said.
How people live in the oldest house of Ufa
In the former house of gold industrials and miners Evdokim and his son Ivan Demidov on the street of the October Revolution 57/1 (formerly the Great Kazan) 18 apartments.
The house of the 18th century has virtually not changed since the time of construction, except for the old age.
Foreign people go here, as on a tour, and the tenants suffer more than they rejoice, from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest Uffim house, the walls of which remember the commander Alexander Suvorov.
The date of construction of the house is inaccurate, historians point to two dates - 1730 and 1737 years.
In any case, it turns out that the building is less than 300 years old.
Old courtyard, always open doors, scaled stairs.
The doors to the apartments are located close to each other, the walls are crushed, and in the lights of the frozen patch the street is seen in places.
Everything seems to be on an honest word.
And the locals say, “You don’t think it is so.”
Living in a wooden house of the 18th century is very difficult, says Tatiana Lukyanova, a resident of apartment No. 3.
The object is in the state reserve, but the money for its content has not been allocated for decades, and we feel as museum exhibits, which the authorities have simply forgotten.
The last repair was 40 years ago.
The walls are still poorly held, but the foundation has all rotted.
Many residents still go to the toilet on the street, and wash once a week in the public bathroom.
How can you be happy in such circumstances?
The road runs right under the windows, there is no pedestrian zone.
Tatiana pushes off the curtain.
Now you can see what was only heard before: a stream of cars under the windows.
You see, the glasses are constantly drizzled, we cannot open the windows, but we are accustomed to the noise.
Man is accustomed to everything, good and bad.
Our apartment is still exemplary, thanks to my husband, his hands are golden.
In addition, we have two rooms, we live three with our son.
And in other families the conditions are much worse, on the second floor generally ceilings slightly more than one and a half meters high.
For contrast, Tatiana offers to visit a neighbor from apartment No. 6 Ludmila Starostina.
A nice hospitality woman from the doorstep offers a cup of coffee and with a sad smile tells:
We have a one-bedroom apartment, 14.5 m2 for four people, so we live: my husband and daughter and granddaughter.
I have been here since birth, there has never been another living space, - Lyudmila surrounds the room with her eyes: an anthrax, two sofas with the letter "g"; on one of them there was a granddaughter with a laptop.
Very close and little different from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, "historical".
But the ceiling regularly flows: the water supply system is not suitable anywhere.
Lyudmila speaks of her apartment daily and surprisingly at the same time, like an Italian whose house stands on Roman ruins.
That is, it reduces to one very old and recent, everyday and legendary:
The water pipeline was built about 40 years ago during the last repair.
Then we made a small kitchen in the corner and a toilet from the former chulan.
We live just where Demidov lived with his family, servants lived on the second floor.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
In the Ufa Real Estate Center, it is said that privatization does not matter.
We only get a one-bedroom apartment, we can't claim more.
We were promised to relocate four months ago, but the promise did not go further.
I am not used to complaining and will not.
In this apartment (room!) lived a whole dynasty: my grandmother and grandfather, my mom and dad, my husband and my daughter and granddaughter.
Everything happened during that time.
For example, healthy rats ran through the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the fleece, they are metric thick!
It is said that the solution was mixed on the eggs, so it lasts so long.
The house is well built, thank you Demidov!
Probably only because so far no one has been killed by a falling ceiling or roof.
Only the building still slowly dies in front of us: the boards and bars of the house rot, the floors repeatedly failed, we poured cement, but everything is useless - the solution goes into the ground, like a well.
It is said that under our room there is a secret pit and a course to the White River, which was specially made by the old believers who once lived here, so that you could hide from danger, in case of anything.
They were persecuted.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how some historian came to them, begging to let him start excavations in the apartment.
And then I persuaded them to give them a living space in exchange for their one in the prospect of October.
Lyudmila rejected the historian:
Where are we all four?
And there is even a small hope that will give housing more space.
If we agreed to an exchange, we would have won nothing.
However, the old family won nothing.
Lyudmila’s greatest dream was that they would be displaced, and that their daughter and 16-year-old granddaughter would be given a separate room.
That is, for two families allocated a two-bedroom apartment instead of the most majestic ruins, in which two generations live now.
Cute, miniature girl Olesya Karsakova from apartments No. 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, in two narrow rooms with a total area of 23 m2, called apartments, lives her large family.
We are seven people, two children.
You can see what conditions.
The fabric rolls out in pieces, like the window frames, in the walls in the kitchen and in the rooms through holes.
The water in the crane is cold all year round.
Walking through the apartments of the oldest house of Ufa, you can make sure that the most lucky spouses Lavrentiev from the apartment No. 4 were.
They occupy the most spacious rooms on the first floor.
You are right, there are lots of places.
A room of 75 squares, prescribed for three people.
We live in the rooms where, according to legend, Suvorov stayed during his stay in Ufa, - says the head of the family Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentiev.
The ceilings are high and spacious.
One bad thing - everything around tears in the seams, collapses, collapses.
Neighbors probably told me.
The most torment we had with the floors: the wooden boards were rotten, the earth was literally going away from underneath our feet.
I put supports, cloves; there is nothing in the hall yet, and in another room we walk, as we swing on the stitches, so everything is shy.
About the house of merchant Evdokim Demidov Alexander Dmitrievich can tell better than any tour guide.
The gold industrialist is treated as a native, speaking about him with admiration.
Indeed, the personality was extraordinary: the owner of the Kagin and Uzyan factories built houses, cast guns and bells, held Ural mines.
Inheritors of commercial real estate are proud of their ancestors, but they no longer want to live under the same roof with history.
I settled here as a child, in the 40s of the 20th century, - says Alexander Dmitrievich.
Then around there were wooden rooms for carriages, barracks and guard houses, subsequently demolished.
In 1968, we wanted to clean up our house, but something stopped us.
The story repeated itself in 2014: we once again attracted new housing.
We, as a team, gathered all the documents, bypassed the necessary instances, and suddenly learned that the move to apartments is postponed for 2015 or 2016.
We no longer believe in all this.
Two years ago Lavrentiev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to learn about the fate of the house.
The resident did not accept.
They sent from one table to another, and then, as a ridicule, issued a paper without signature and seal: "The Ministry of Culture does not object to the resettlement of residents."
I even had the feeling that our house has long been out of the city plan, because at first it was under the number 57, then it became 57 A, and now 57/1.
It was as if it had already been destroyed in the 1970s.
"Russkaya planeta" addressed the head of the information and analytical work sector of the Ufa Land Resources Administration Vladimir Barabas.
The house on the street of October Revolution 57/1 is included in the program of resettlement of old housing.
I cannot be held accountable for the actions of officials of the 1970s, but I know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all the old houses, despite the historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities - to restore all the old houses on the street of the October Revolution, which represent architectural value - is successfully carried out.
The residents are expected to move into new apartments soon.
According to Barabash, the restoration of the House of Demidov will be Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice.
Now in Italy is taking place the architectural Biennale, and the project "Old Ufa" is presented there among others.
I hope that by 2016 the entire former Old Kazan Street will be restored, says the official.
Houses will acquire a proper appearance, corresponding to the one that was before, three centuries ago.
Demidov’s house is likely to become a museum open to all.
In addition, at the government level, it has been decided to make the street pedestrian on weekends.
Unfortunately, it will not work, too much traffic on the roads in the city.
To relocate people from the future museum Vladimir Barabash promises in 2015.
However, they are unlikely to be satisfied: their new apartments will be the same area as the current ones.
Only from another era.
