4 tips on how to the best quality of underwater photos and videos
If you want to photograph or film underwater, there are a number of equipment options.
The cheapest option is a waterproof soap, such as the Nikon Coolpix AW120, or an action camera, such as the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both of which are sold for about $300.
I took these photos on a family holiday with several cameras, all at a cost of about $350.
Regardless of the equipment you use, there are a few rules to follow in order to the best results.
Check your equipment.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure that the camera’s battery and other compartments are tightly closed.
Additionally, adjust your camera for the type of photos or videos you are going to take.
Some camera and video cameras have shooting modes or object type that optimize exposure for darkened underwater conditions.
And before jumping into the water, figure out how deep your equipment can descend.
Some cameras are designed for just 5 feet, others for 50 or 60 feet.
Check out our buyer guide and digital camera ratings for both traditional and waterproof models.
Take a few shots – because many of them won’t work.
Soaphouses have LCDs that will help you assemble photos, while action cameras usually don’t.
Even if you have a LCD, it will be difficult to see underwater, and setting up the frame will be a random process.
Make a few cadres.
Also, if your camera has a serial shooting mode that captures several frames with slightly different exposure settings, use it.
Stay at the surface.
The amount of light decreases significantly the deeper you dive underwater.
If possible, stay on the surface when shooting in a pool, river or ocean.
It will also allow you to convey more colors on photos; the deeper you go, the less colors you will see.
Swim closer to the objects.
This is a great tip for shooting on land, but it’s even more important underwater due to dark light conditions.
Especially important if you’re shooting on an action camera: This equipment is often fitted with a fixed, wide-angle lens, which means you’ll have to approach the objects of the shooting if you want to fill the frame.
