It was mesothelioma, an incurable cancer that affects the pleura, or lungs.
For most cancers, it is difficult to find out the exact cause.
Although some smokers get lung cancer, for example, not all lung cancer patients smoked.
But with mesothelioma differently.
In almost all cases, the cause is the contact with asbestos, a fiber-shaped building material that was once called a "miracle", but which is now known to be deadly.
For most of us, mesothelioma is a disease that can be ignored.
Asbestos, after all, is a material from the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in the UK since the 1960s, when a recommended industrial ban came into force.
Even when it was used, only people from specific industries worked in close contact with it: pipe insulators, builders, carpenters and dock workers, for example.
An industrial toxin from another era, it is hardly seen as a cause for concern today.
This calm is wrong.
Britain, it turns out, is today at the peak of the mesothelioma epidemic.
More people die from mesothelioma here than in any other country on the planet.
With an annual death rate of approximately 2,500 people, more than twice as many people die from this disease than from car accidents.
Annual deaths from mesothelioma since 1980 and forecast future deaths in the UK
The reason we are feeling its deadly consequences now is that while the use of asbestos has been illegal for many years (all types of asbestos were eventually banned by law in 1999), it usually takes tens of years to develop mesothelioma.
And attacking mesotheliomes is not limited to veterans of industrial construction specialties.
Asbestos has been, and in many cases remains, placed in the houses where we live, the offices where we work, the schools where we study, and the shops where we go shopping.
As a result, mesothelioma does not pay attention to class, level of wealth, profession or age.
The bastions of the elect, from fashionable London supermarkets to private schools, turned out to be not the salvation.
The parliamentary building is filled with asbestos.
Even the hospitals that are intended to treat us have turned out to be reservoirs of this deadly carcinogen.
Andrew Lawson was not old.
He was not a tube insulator.
In fact, he had to think about where he could come into contact with asbestos.
Then he understood.
"It seems that there may have been a lot of asbestos in the tunnels at the Gaia Hospital where I spent six years on an internship," he wrote.
Everyone—students, nurses, doctors, and truckers—used these tunnels.
I wonder how many of my peers will get the same disease?
This was a question to which, unfortunately, he could give a partial answer.
“Of the four doctors who have trained at Gaia Hospital and subsequently developed mesothelioma over the past five years,” he noted in a letter in 2010, “I am the only one who has survived.”
How many of us will suffer from this disease?
Andrew Lawson was diagnosed with mesothelioma when he was 48.
When he died on February 17, he was 55.
Living so long is unusual.
