The electric car market in Russia is just forming - in 2013 around 100 electric vehicles were sold across the country.
At the beginning of 2014 zero import duty on electric vehicles, so sales will be about 500 units, predicts Mitsubishi Motors chief executive officer in Russia Andrei Pankov.
But the five-fold growth does not make electric cars any noticeable: in 2013 in Russia, according to the Association of European Business, sold 2.78 million passenger cars and light commercial vehicles.
For now, only Mitsubishi Motors imports electric cars to Russia.
Renault is preparing to start imports – the company focuses primarily on corporate customers, says Nicola Remiz, Director of Strategic Planning and Partnerships of Renault in Russia.
Most other electric transport manufacturers have taken a stand-by position towards Russia.
Developments of electric vehicles are also in Russian manufacturers - "", GAZ, "", but the output is miserable.
For example, in January-July 2014, according to the "ASM-holding", "AutoVAZ" produced 30 electric vehicles.
Demand is low due to the cost of electric vehicles, acknowledges the director of "AutoVAZ" engineering Sergey Amanov, without state support the breakthrough in this segment will not be.
The development of the Russian electric vehicle market in addition to the cost of cars (those electric cars sold in Russia are on average twice as expensive as analogues with internal combustion engines) contains the underdevelopment of charging infrastructure (fuels - units), says General Director of "AutoStata" Sergey Celikov.
Due to the cost and low rates of cost decrease, electric cars in the next 3-4 years will remain a niche segment of the Russian market, forecasts the editor-in-chief of "Autorevy" Mikhail Podorozhansky, Celikov agrees with him.
Automotive manufacturers, on the contrary, say that some models of electric cars are already close to the cost of conventional cars.
The Russian electric car market has good prospects, the main thing is to instill confidence in consumers that "electromobility" is real; this, in particular, will contribute to the emergence of new charging stations, emphasizes the president of the BMW Group in Russia Wolfgang Schlime.
Such infrastructure projects are implemented, for example, by the state company "Rosseti": several stations have been built in Moscow, soon there will be about 80 more.
Negotiations on the construction of the gas network are also being conducted with other regions.
According to the director of the department "Rosnety" Vladimir Sophyn, the company believes in the market of electric vehicles and is ready to build gas stations across the country, but there are also problems: a small number of electric vehicles in the country and the lack of a single standard for charging electric vehicles of different brands.
In addition, "Rosetti" as a network company does not have the right to deal with the sale of electricity, the possibility of doing so in relation to charging electric vehicles is being worked out.
Pankov believes that the most effective measure of state support for the formation of the electric vehicle market in Russia is zero customs duties.
The zero rate will be valid until the end of 2014, the possibility of its extension and the extension of the preferential list is being worked out.
The replacement of the transport tax for environmental (the idea is discussed and applies to all cars) will also support the market, but not as tangible as customs preferences, Pankov believes.
The transport tax in Russia is small, says Pankov, unlike, for example, Norway, where the reduction of the tax has led to a sharp increase in sales of electric vehicles - now they account for 12% of the market.
In Russia, stimulating measures are also needed for car owners, such as free parking in the city center (as already done in Moscow), Pankov is convinced, or the possibility of moving electric vehicles along dedicated lanes, which in Russia is not yet.
