Carrie Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking that she had only a few years to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Touty’s disease (CMD) – a group of hereditary disorders that lead to nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with STD because so little is known about the condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are believed to have CT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, uncertain walking, and compressed toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition is not healed and progresses, meaning the symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedrich ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
