Tax burden on entrepreneurs in Washington Zone increases as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country increased moderately last year as the economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington Zone are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia combined paid $27.6 billion to the state and local treasury in fiscal 2013, 3.8 percent more than $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on by state and local level increased by 4.3 percent last year, to $671 billion, compared to 3.9 percent a year earlier, and this was the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years when bills declined, in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes grew faster, 4.3 percent than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by a professional service firm, Ernst & Young and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county’s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from entrepreneurial taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland’s tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the lowest amount of tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
The growth in tax revenues is largely driven by a return to the company’s previous level of real estate value, the researchers say, which raised real estate taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three consecutive years of growth of less than 1 percent.
While a large proportion of these revenue comes from large states such as California, New York and Texas, it seems that the same is happening in the Washington Zone.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia combined paid $10 billion in state and local real estate taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012, an increase of 4.2 percent from the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate value has no similar effect on state and local tax revenue growth in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one-fifth of corporate tax accounts.
Companies in Virginia and District of Columbia pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of real estate taxes.
“What’s happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, belongs either to the government or to a non-profit organization that doesn’t pay real estate taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Taxation Center.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more on, for example, income taxes to pay for the same services that are available in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs' incomes also appear to be going to the correction, according to these data.
Companies in the region declared corporate income tax at the state level of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland has raised $1 billion in corporate income tax revenues, the largest in the region.
Although trends are directed in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three locations.
Growth in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average, 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below average of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of three jurisdictions (each of which has the same corporate rate) of 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high – 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes for entrepreneurs by state and locally and, overall, a more favorable tax climate for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The district was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is experiencing competitive pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina recently signed a legislation lowering corporate interest rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, just like in Virginia, and the rate will fall to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to tax revenue targets next year, this law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to even 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small in the Washington Area seem to feel better and thus pay more taxes across the state and locally, according to a recent study.
Entrepreneurial taxes paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners – the transitional structure under which most small firms are organized – in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia increased by 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, at a much faster growth rate than entrepreneurial taxes overall.
Researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to persist this year, with state and local government turnover tax revenue rising by 6.2 percent over the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington Zone may be lagging behind as the decline in federal spending affects the region’s labor market.
