MEPs propose to speed up the entry into force of the law on personal data
If the initiative succeeds, the data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015.
The State Duma has submitted a draft law, which provides for the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is placed in the legislative activity base of the lower house.
Its authors were Deputies of the State Duma Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fedorov (United Russia), Vladimir Parakhin (Just Russia) and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a more prompt and effective provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the preservation of personal data and compliance with the secret of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, the entry into force of which is rushing parliamentarians, obliges to store on the territory of the Russian Federation the personal data of Russians processed through the Internet.
It also makes compulsory the recording, systematization, accumulation, storage, clarification and extraction of personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation, as well as the indication of information on the location of such databases.
In addition, the law grants Roskomnadzor the right, on the basis of a court decision, to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of the so-called "black lists" of violating sites - an automated information system "Register of violators of the rights of personal data subjects".
The law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoy and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the KPRF.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in the Russian Federation will have to pay the rent.
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State Duma today, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy Leonid Levin said that he does not see problems to postpone the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own storage of personal data of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "from Rostelecom, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers in lease and already provides their servers, from Mail Group, from Western companies, which today already provide their servers."
“There are also several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area,” he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to operate in the territory of the Russian Federation, I do not see problems - they will get technological capabilities for placement," Levin summed up.
Controversial bill
Immediately after the publication of the bill, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that if the bill was passed, Russians would no longer be able to use many global internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking of air tickets and hotels.
According to the association, “the bill deprives subjects of personal data – citizens of the Russian Federation of the right to dispose of their own data imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation”.
The statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be the creation of a mechanism to inform the user about where the recording is carried out, the systematization of his personal data.
In this case, it will be able to choose on which territory these actions will be carried out.
The adoption of similar bills on the "localization" of personal data in other countries has led to the departure of global services and to significant economic losses.
