The savings certificate will be named and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban savings certificates on the applicant, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of the irrevocable contribution.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will prohibit savings certificates for the applicant.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as rates here are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that savings certificates for the applicant do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they cost the bank cheaper, since there is no need to make deductions to the Deposit Insurance Agency (ASV) fund.
The pitch of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and Sberbank and Bank of Moscow will suffer from it, which, according to the estimates of ASV, control 98% of the profile market.
Moreover, the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to estimates of the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in the ASV, is that clients of a small bank, who bought such a certificate, in case of withdrawal of licenses from it try to get money in the ASV.
Some depositors, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying savings certificates on the depository, may assume that their investments are insured.
Justified absence of insurance payments on these certificates in case of withdrawal of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency there have been cases when holders of applicant certificates tried to collect insurance compensation through the court", - stated in the ASV.
The problem is, of course, invented.
After all, no one will pay the buyers of certificates anyway, since they have no right to compensation from the state according to the law.
If it were that the instrument was not insured in the ASV, along with it would be banned and metal accounts, on which the funds of citizens are accounted in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but no one attempts to exist yet.
The fact, most likely, is that certificates on the applicant are a very convenient securities, which can actually act as a quaside money.
At the same time, their movement is virtually uncontrollable: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer it to any citizen, and before the liquidation of such a certificate can change many owners.
It is not by chance that the bill stipulates that the savings certificate must be a nominal securities, which should be stored in the depository.
And to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to issue without the right to early repayment.
That is, the analogue of the irrevocable contribution that banks have long dreamed of is introduced.
