iPhone becomes a wallet
On the eve of September 9, when Apple is due to present its new developments, new leaks appear in the press about what to expect from the presentation.
U.S. media reports that the sixth-generation iPhone will be equipped with a mobile wallet function as a result of a joint Apple project and payment systems Visa, MasterCard and American Express.
According to Bloomberg and the specialized Internet resource Re/code, at the presentation of new products on September 9, Apple may, among other things, announce a joint project with Visa, MasterCard and American Express, resulting in the new smartphone iPhone 6 will be available mobile wallet function.
The companies themselves declined to comment on this.
This feature allows you to make payment at the store’s cashier with the help of a smartphone.
Payment will be identified by the user by his fingerprint using Touch ID.
It is that the iPhone will be built into NFC (near field communication) technology for the first time, which allows to make contactless payments using the smartphone and the corresponding reader on the cash.
The NFC technology itself will be available thanks to a dedicated microprocessor from the Dutch high-tech company NXP (formerly Philips Semiconductors).
For the first time, NFC was introduced in 2004 as part of a collaboration between Sony, Nokia, Philips Semiconductors and more than a hundred other companies in the so-called NFC Forum - an association to promote this technology.
The first phone with NFC was released by Nokia in 2006.
The first smartphone on Android with NFC function – Samsung Nexus S – was introduced in 2010.
In May 2011, Google introduced the Google Wallet system, which allows users to link bank cards to their Google account and pay using their Android smartphone.
However, American experts emphasize that, despite the large investments of high-tech companies in the promotion of NFC technology, American retailers are still cautious about the innovation and are not too willing to spend money on equipping their stores with such systems.
Therefore, now the observers hope that Apple's entry into this market will still force retailers to accelerate and more actively implement this technology in their stores.
