SCR stopped the investigation of the Tu-204 disaster in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (СКР) has terminated the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the aircraft Tu-204 of the airline Red Wings.
This is by the press service of the Ministry.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and the boarding engineer.
Judicial examination showed that the cause of the disaster was increased speed of landing, failure of the crew to perform the standard procedures at landing, as well as the unintentional output of engines on increased rotations of direct traction.
The Tu-204 of the airline Red Wings, following the Prague-Moscow flight, crashed on December 29, 2012 when landing at Moscow's Vnukovo airport.
The aircraft crossed the runway and burned.
At the scene of the accident, the aircraft commander, the second pilot and the boarding engineer were killed.
Two passengers were transported to medical facilities, where they subsequently died from their injuries.
Three other passengers, hospitalized with severe bodily injuries, were undergoing long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car, which was moving at the time of the disaster on the Kyiv highway, received serious bodily injuries.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
After the crash, the transport prosecutor's office conducted a check at Red Wings, during which numerous violations were detected.
In February 2013, the airline’s license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
