Anger is the most universal and functional human emotion.
Angry facial expression is biologically universal for humanity, and every organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but is an additional means of expression of power and threat, Australian and US scientists have found out.
They about their findings in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and they can be read briefly in the press release of the University of California in Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face - the sloped and lowered eyebrows, the stretched lips in a thin line, the swollen nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and is made even by birth blind children who have never seen it, notes lead author of the study Aaron Sell.
As part of a large research project dedicated to the nature of anger, scientists found that this emotion arose to effectively lead disputes during conflict.
The more physical harm one person can inflict on another, the more ability he has to dictate his conditions, and he communicates this to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
The researchers found confirmation for another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to get angry and move to handicraft, consider themselves entitled to impose unfavourable conditions on others, and also prefer the force methods of conflict resolution to peaceful ones.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily a “trade emotion”, the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create the angry expression of the face should represent the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor – and thus force as soon as possible to agree with his conditions in order to avoid conflict.
To verify this hypothesis, the researchers modeled the face on the computer, where each of the seven elements of the angry face was present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although the lowered eyebrows or forwarded beard separately did not make the face angry, the physically stronger person depicted with such traits was unanimously admitted by the study participants.
Human anger, as in animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one’s own strength, forcing one to agree and obey.
A person blows up the nostrils and presses his lips for the same purpose as a frog that blows up, or a babouin that demonstrates his kicks.
Anger is triggered by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form, most effectively demonstrating to the opposite side the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing," said anthropologist John Tubi.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the TV radio company "Crimea"
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate in 2014 from the federal budget 250 million rubles to the autonomous non-profit organization "Teleradio Company "Crimea".
This is stated in the draft government decree prepared by the department, which was familiarized with "Lenta.ru".
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the expenses of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the acquisition of equipment".
In particular, the allocated money is intended to re-equip the hardware-studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video server.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of the fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the federal budget provided for the Ministry of Communications.
Crimea was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
Today, the television signal coverage of the company is more than 75 percent of the peninsula.
In 2011, the Crimean Television Company obtained a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
